WEBVTT

00:06.208 --> 00:07.916
-[clock ticking faintly]
-[water lapping]

00:49.666 --> 00:50.958
[muffled] Mom!

00:51.916 --> 00:53.291
[ticking grows louder]

00:54.166 --> 00:55.500
[uneasy music playing]

01:00.708 --> 01:01.916
[water splashes]

01:07.250 --> 01:09.541
[music continues
under ticking sound]

01:26.916 --> 01:28.625
-[chess clock button clicks]
-[ticking stops]

01:31.291 --> 01:33.875
[joyful orchestral music playing]

01:42.291 --> 01:43.166
Well, now.

01:43.750 --> 01:44.583
[chuckles]

01:45.458 --> 01:46.541
Welcome.

01:52.208 --> 01:53.916
[thoughtful piano music playing]

02:11.541 --> 02:14.666
-[woman on TV] Got a cigarette, doctor?
-[doctor on TV] Sorry, I…

02:14.750 --> 02:15.625
[TV clicks off]

02:27.250 --> 02:28.916
I asked for a pleasant room,

02:29.541 --> 02:31.208
and I believe they gave me one.

02:33.541 --> 02:35.375
[laughing]

02:39.583 --> 02:41.041
[elevator bell dings]

02:42.875 --> 02:44.875
[indistinct conversations]

03:05.333 --> 03:07.500
-I'm Beth.
-Harmon. Kentucky State Champion.

03:07.583 --> 03:08.625
Nice to meet you.

03:09.708 --> 03:13.375
There are two games a day,
and the time control is 120/40.

03:14.916 --> 03:17.500
You get two hours to make 40 moves.

03:21.250 --> 03:22.541
Welcome to Cincinnati.

03:23.166 --> 03:24.000
Thank you.

03:25.708 --> 03:29.208
And the rook comes to the seventh rank.

03:29.916 --> 03:30.958
That right there…

03:32.083 --> 03:33.875
that is a bone in the throat.

03:34.625 --> 03:38.125
Guy takes one look at this,
he pays up, 20 bucks.

03:38.208 --> 03:40.458
The Caro-Kann Defense, genuine bummer.

03:41.125 --> 03:42.541
What's wrong with Caro-Kann?

03:44.291 --> 03:46.291
It's all pawns and no hope.

03:47.916 --> 03:51.250
Here, look, I'll show you, all right?
This is Caro-Kann.

03:51.333 --> 03:53.291
-[chess pieces clatter]
-I'd take the knight.

03:56.333 --> 03:57.208
You're, um…

03:59.625 --> 04:02.041
Aren't you that kid from Kentucky
who wiped out Harry Beltik?

04:02.125 --> 04:04.875
If you take his knight,
then you double his pawns.

04:05.791 --> 04:08.708
Big deal. Like I said, it's all pawns…

04:09.500 --> 04:10.666
and no hope.

04:11.291 --> 04:13.125
Let me show you how you win with Black.

04:14.166 --> 04:15.583
Watch this.

04:18.583 --> 04:19.791
What does White do here?

04:20.416 --> 04:23.291
-[Beth, man 1] Queen takes pawn.
-[man 2] Queen takes pawn.

04:25.375 --> 04:27.458
Rook to king eight. Check.

04:27.541 --> 04:28.500
Queen falls.

04:29.333 --> 04:30.916
-That’s Mieses-Reshevsky.
-[man 2] Yeah.

04:31.000 --> 04:33.583
-[man 1] From the '30s.
-Very good. Margate, 1935.

04:34.541 --> 04:37.958
-White played rook to queen one.
-What else has he got?

04:39.291 --> 04:40.416
All right, I gotta go.

04:41.500 --> 04:42.458
Hey, you know what?

04:43.833 --> 04:45.708
Reshevsky, he was playing like that…

04:46.333 --> 04:48.750
back when he was your age, little girl.

04:49.958 --> 04:50.833
Or even younger.

04:54.833 --> 04:55.666
Are you playing?

04:56.500 --> 04:57.333
Oh, what, here?

04:59.083 --> 05:00.791
Nah, nah.

05:01.833 --> 05:04.208
Just come through, see some old friends.

05:05.416 --> 05:08.333
And plus, playing too many opens…

05:08.958 --> 05:11.083
it can only hurt me, you know what I mean?

05:12.208 --> 05:13.041
Good luck.

05:21.375 --> 05:22.291
-Hello.
-Hello.

05:22.375 --> 05:24.000
Beth Harmon. Where am I playing?

05:25.250 --> 05:26.958
It's table 15, right over there.

05:28.791 --> 05:30.166
-Thank you.
-You're welcome.

05:36.958 --> 05:39.250
-Beth Harmon.
-Shit.

05:45.333 --> 05:46.375
-[Beth] Hey!
-[man] Stupid…

05:46.458 --> 05:48.500
-Harmon?
-What are you two doing here?

05:49.416 --> 05:50.500
Losing mostly.

05:51.083 --> 05:54.000
We're on the university team now.
Second and third alternate.

05:54.500 --> 05:56.791
Oh, I'm sorry we won't get to play.

05:56.875 --> 05:59.833
[scoffs] We're not.
You destroy everyone you play, Harmon.

06:00.625 --> 06:03.333
-I can only lose so much.
-[chuckles] That's the truth.

06:03.833 --> 06:06.250
-[Mrs. Wheatley laughing]
-I said slow down!

06:11.250 --> 06:13.000
[man speaks indistinctly on TV]

06:14.375 --> 06:17.041
[woman 1] Isn't that skating rink
a little close to the bowling alley?

06:17.125 --> 06:18.625
-[Mrs. Wheatley laughing]
-Do you mind?

06:18.708 --> 06:21.250
-[laughing] Sorry.
-[woman 2] It works out. You see, it…

06:21.333 --> 06:25.166
It keeps the bowlers cool,
and you automatically…

06:25.250 --> 06:26.375
[TV volume lowers]

06:26.458 --> 06:27.416
What are you doing?

06:27.958 --> 06:29.541
[Beth] Replaying my earlier games.

06:30.041 --> 06:31.666
What on earth for?

06:31.750 --> 06:33.708
Looking for weaknesses in my play.

06:33.791 --> 06:35.166
[TV continues softly]

06:35.250 --> 06:36.083
I see.

06:37.333 --> 06:38.166
And?

06:39.458 --> 06:40.500
[Beth] There aren't any.

06:42.416 --> 06:43.250
Good girl.

06:44.250 --> 06:47.166
-[gentle orchestral music playing]
-[chess pieces clacking]

07:29.375 --> 07:30.625
[onlookers applauding]

07:36.125 --> 07:38.291
It's so much more exciting
than I imagined.

07:38.375 --> 07:39.833
Did you watch the whole game?

07:40.416 --> 07:41.333
Of course.

07:41.416 --> 07:42.250
[man] Beth.

07:44.083 --> 07:46.833
When he brought out his rook,
then took that pawn…

07:48.000 --> 07:50.333
I thought you were done for.
I should have known better.

07:50.416 --> 07:51.500
Yes, you should have.

07:51.583 --> 07:52.500
[man chuckles]

07:52.583 --> 07:53.416
Elizabeth,

07:54.000 --> 07:56.375
aren't you going to introduce me
to your friends?

07:56.458 --> 07:57.708
[Beth] Sorry.

07:57.791 --> 07:59.583
Matt, Mike, this is my mom.

08:00.750 --> 08:02.083
Mike, nice to meet you.

08:02.166 --> 08:03.791
-Nice to meet you.
-And I'm Matt.

08:03.875 --> 08:06.041
-Mm. A pleasure.
-[Matt] Nice to meet you.

08:08.000 --> 08:11.041
Well, I don't know about you young people,
but I'm famished.

08:11.125 --> 08:14.416
-There's a restaurant in the hotel lobby.
-Mm. Show us the way?

08:14.500 --> 08:15.333
Sure.

08:18.000 --> 08:20.625
I can't make up my mind
which one is more handsome.

08:23.333 --> 08:25.000
I'd like to play in the US Open.

08:25.583 --> 08:26.458
You might win it.

08:27.083 --> 08:28.833
Would that lead to playing abroad?

08:29.500 --> 08:30.625
In Europe, I mean?

08:30.708 --> 08:33.666
No reason why not. They have to know you
before they invite you.

08:33.750 --> 08:35.750
Would winning the Open
make them know about me?

08:35.833 --> 08:36.708
[Matt] Hell yes!

08:36.791 --> 08:40.375
Benny Watts plays in Europe all the time
now that he has his international title.

08:40.875 --> 08:42.041
How's the prize money?

08:42.750 --> 08:45.625
-[Matt] Pretty good, I think.
-Hm? What's pretty good?

08:46.250 --> 08:47.250
More than in the States.

08:48.083 --> 08:49.208
What about Russia?

08:50.208 --> 08:51.458
The Soviets are murder.

08:51.541 --> 08:53.166
They eat Americans for breakfast there.

08:53.250 --> 08:57.166
I don't think there's been an American
with a prayer against them in 20 years.

08:57.791 --> 08:58.666
It's like ballet.

08:58.750 --> 09:00.666
They pay people to play chess.

09:02.416 --> 09:04.750
We should probably go.
We don't wanna be late.

09:04.833 --> 09:06.416
This one's for all the marbles.

09:07.583 --> 09:09.583
Five hundred of them to be exact.

09:09.666 --> 09:11.708
[thrilling music playing quietly]

09:11.791 --> 09:13.958
[Matt] That's Rudolph. He's a master.

09:14.041 --> 09:16.291
-[chess clock button clicks]
-[clock ticking]

09:22.958 --> 09:26.333
Beth cannot be happy
about being crowded into an ending

09:26.416 --> 09:28.583
with a rook, a knight, and three pawns.

09:30.333 --> 09:31.416
It's so complicated.

09:34.125 --> 09:35.000
[Matt] Uh-oh.

09:35.958 --> 09:37.125
And that's check.

09:40.750 --> 09:42.000
And that's mate.

09:46.333 --> 09:47.458
[onlookers applauding]

09:49.166 --> 09:52.250
I've allowed 12 dollars
for our celebration supper tonight,

09:52.333 --> 09:55.041
and two dollars for a small breakfast
in the morning.

09:55.625 --> 09:59.625
That makes our total expenses,
so far, $172.30.

09:59.708 --> 10:02.333
Which leaves over 300 dollars.

10:03.875 --> 10:04.708
Beth…

10:08.583 --> 10:09.583
I was thinking…

10:12.333 --> 10:16.166
perhaps you could give me 10%,
as an agent's commission?

10:22.958 --> 10:24.541
Let's make it 15%.

10:27.000 --> 10:29.458
Which would be 49 dollars and 54 cents.

10:32.083 --> 10:34.583
They told me at Methuen
you were marvelous at math.

10:38.750 --> 10:41.583
[Mrs. Wheatley] "Schoolgirl beats
Grandmaster in Pittsburgh."

10:42.083 --> 10:45.833
"Onlookers were amazed
at her youthful fine points of strategy."

10:46.458 --> 10:50.250
"She shows the assurance
of a player twice her age."

10:53.041 --> 10:54.833
That's national recognition, dear.

10:55.791 --> 10:57.500
I'm afraid she's had a bit of a relapse.

10:57.583 --> 11:00.333
The doctor wants to keep her in bed
for a few more days.

11:03.541 --> 11:05.375
I'm sure she'll be better by Monday.

11:05.916 --> 11:08.208
One of the worst colds
I've ever seen in a child.

11:08.291 --> 11:09.333
The poor dear.

11:10.458 --> 11:12.041
[whispering] We're gonna be late.

11:12.958 --> 11:13.791
Yeah.

11:14.375 --> 11:15.500
Lots of liquids.

11:17.041 --> 11:19.041
-Thank you.
-[flight attendant] You're welcome.

11:24.333 --> 11:27.916
There's a tournament in Houston
over the holidays, starting on the 26th.

11:32.291 --> 11:34.958
I understand it's very easy
to travel on Christmas Day

11:35.041 --> 11:37.958
since most people are home
eating plum pudding or whatever.

11:39.458 --> 11:40.833
[Beth] I saw that one, too.

11:44.333 --> 11:46.083
I believe we could fly to Houston,

11:46.666 --> 11:49.208
have a very pleasant
winter vacation in the sun.

11:50.708 --> 11:51.916
Do girly things.

11:53.041 --> 11:55.958
I hear they have
a very lovely beauty spa at the hotel.

11:58.875 --> 11:59.708
Yes, Mother.

12:12.458 --> 12:14.583
She has a fever of 101.

12:14.666 --> 12:16.958
-Must be the flu.
-[TV playing indistinctly]

12:17.041 --> 12:19.166
She won't be back
until after the holidays.

12:19.791 --> 12:21.958
["25th of the 12th"
by Bill Compton playing]

12:22.041 --> 12:23.916
♪ On the 25th of the 12th ♪

12:24.458 --> 12:26.458
♪ The 25th of the 12th ♪

12:27.083 --> 12:30.583
♪ When Rudolph makes his yearly ride… ♪

12:30.666 --> 12:32.833
They're calling you a wunderkind.

12:35.583 --> 12:37.791
I might have to start keeping a scrapbook.

12:40.416 --> 12:41.250
How's your meal?

12:42.375 --> 12:44.916
This might be
the best Christmas I've ever had.

12:45.000 --> 12:47.000
[Mrs. Wheatley laughs]

12:47.666 --> 12:52.333
♪ …and when it's time to say
Good night ♪

12:52.916 --> 12:55.250
♪ Then all the stars we trust ♪

12:55.333 --> 12:57.541
♪ Will sprinkle twinkle dust ♪

12:57.625 --> 13:01.666
♪ Over every flag of wine ♪

13:02.625 --> 13:05.000
♪ What a wonderful holiday ♪

13:05.666 --> 13:08.500
-♪ With bells on every sleigh… ♪
-[coughs] It's good.

13:09.458 --> 13:10.375
Is that a martini?

13:11.333 --> 13:12.166
Gibson.

13:13.125 --> 13:15.750
I find the onion
slightly more refined than the olive.

13:15.833 --> 13:17.791
♪ If you'd ever wish yourself ♪

13:17.875 --> 13:20.208
♪ On the 25th of the 12th ♪

13:20.791 --> 13:22.791
♪ Santa will share his wealth ♪

13:22.875 --> 13:26.083
♪ On the 25th of the 12th this year ♪

13:28.583 --> 13:30.791
I should probably learn
how to speak Russian.

13:32.291 --> 13:34.000
Do they teach that at Fairfield?

13:34.791 --> 13:37.416
I'd have to take a night class
at the junior college.

13:41.500 --> 13:43.375
The kids would all be older than you.

13:44.291 --> 13:46.208
And by kids, I mean boys.

13:51.708 --> 13:53.375
[woman] They say you're the real thing.

13:53.458 --> 13:55.541
That's it, honey,
hold it up so we can see it.

13:56.166 --> 13:58.625
So, can you tell
the readers of Life how it feels?

13:59.833 --> 14:02.625
I mean, to be a girl among all those men?

14:03.416 --> 14:04.583
I don't mind it.

14:04.666 --> 14:05.958
[reporter] Isn't it intimidating?

14:06.041 --> 14:09.666
I mean, when I was a girl,
I wasn't allowed to be competitive.

14:09.750 --> 14:11.583
-I played with dolls.
-[camera shutter clicking]

14:11.666 --> 14:14.458
-Chess isn't always competitive.
-No, but you play to win.

14:14.541 --> 14:17.375
Yes, but chess can also be…

14:18.250 --> 14:19.083
What?

14:20.875 --> 14:21.958
Beautiful.

14:26.125 --> 14:27.125
You're an orphan, Beth.

14:28.750 --> 14:29.791
Yes, I know that.

14:29.875 --> 14:33.416
No, yes, of course you do.
I was wondering how you learned to play.

14:33.500 --> 14:35.666
-Mr. Shaibel taught me.
-[camera shutter clicking]

14:36.291 --> 14:39.375
He was the janitor at Methuen.

14:39.458 --> 14:40.958
A janitor taught you how to play?

14:41.041 --> 14:43.208
-Really?
-When I was eight.

14:43.291 --> 14:44.166
I imagine…

14:45.000 --> 14:49.666
it must have been such a distraction
from life in such a depressing place.

14:51.625 --> 14:53.208
You must have been very lonely.

14:54.416 --> 14:55.500
I'm fine being alone.

14:57.208 --> 15:00.333
Do you imagine
that you saw the king as a father,

15:00.958 --> 15:02.583
and the queen as a mother?

15:02.666 --> 15:05.375
I mean, one to attack, one to protect?

15:06.041 --> 15:07.541
They're just pieces.

15:08.041 --> 15:11.000
-[camera shutter clicks]
-And it was the board I noticed first.

15:11.083 --> 15:11.916
The board?

15:12.791 --> 15:13.625
[Beth] Yes.

15:14.458 --> 15:17.666
It's an entire world of just 64 squares.

15:18.375 --> 15:19.416
I feel…

15:19.500 --> 15:21.375
safe in it.

15:23.000 --> 15:25.625
I can control it, I can dominate it.

15:27.666 --> 15:28.791
And it's predictable.

15:29.625 --> 15:30.541
[camera shutter clicks]

15:31.041 --> 15:33.166
So, if I get hurt,
I only have myself to blame.

15:33.250 --> 15:34.250
[camera shutter clicks]

15:34.750 --> 15:35.583
How interesting.

15:38.291 --> 15:39.958
Tell me, Elizabeth.

15:41.208 --> 15:43.666
Have you ever heard
of something called apophenia?

15:44.208 --> 15:45.375
No, what's that?

15:45.458 --> 15:49.625
It's the finding of pattern or meaning
where other people don't.

15:50.666 --> 15:56.083
Sometimes, people with this condition
get feelings of revelation or ecstasies.

15:56.916 --> 16:01.250
Sometimes, people find patterns or meaning
where there aren't any.

16:01.791 --> 16:03.916
Hm. What does that have to do with me?

16:04.000 --> 16:06.291
Creativity and psychosis
often go hand in hand.

16:06.375 --> 16:07.583
[camera shutter clicks]

16:07.666 --> 16:10.166
Or, for that matter, genius and madness.

16:10.833 --> 16:12.000
[camera shutter clicks]

16:13.250 --> 16:14.541
You think I'm crazy?

16:14.625 --> 16:17.250
-No, of course not. I was just asking--
-I think that's enough.

16:18.000 --> 16:19.416
Beth has homework to finish.

16:19.958 --> 16:22.625
She is, after all,
still a young woman in school.

16:23.125 --> 16:26.833
-Just like all the other kids her age.
-[reporter] Of course. [clears throat]

16:27.333 --> 16:29.583
-It was an honor to meet you.
-Thanks.

16:31.083 --> 16:32.166
You know…

16:33.750 --> 16:35.333
you might try bridge.

16:35.416 --> 16:38.208
-I hear a lot of chess players enjoy it.
-I'll show you out.

16:42.791 --> 16:43.833
[sighs in annoyance]

16:44.375 --> 16:47.291
-[indistinct conversations]
-[live jazz music plays softly]

16:47.875 --> 16:50.583
[Mrs. Wheatley]
"With some people, chess is a pastime."

16:50.666 --> 16:53.583
"With others, it is a compulsion,
even an addiction."

16:54.250 --> 16:56.125
"And every now and then,
a person comes along

16:56.208 --> 16:57.458
for whom it is a birthright."

16:58.166 --> 17:01.916
"Now and then, a small boy appears
and dazzles us with his precocity,

17:02.000 --> 17:05.041
at what may be
the world's most difficult game."

17:05.125 --> 17:07.208
"But what if that boy were a girl?"

17:08.375 --> 17:13.250
"A young, unsmiling girl, with brown eyes,
red hair, and a dark blue dress?"

17:14.500 --> 17:15.833
We started a chess club.

17:16.333 --> 17:18.166
"Into the male-dominated world

17:18.250 --> 17:20.500
of the nation's top chess tournaments,

17:20.583 --> 17:24.041
strolls a teenage girl
with bright, intense eyes,

17:24.125 --> 17:26.916
from Fairfield High School
in Lexington, Kentucky."

17:27.000 --> 17:29.333
"She is quiet, well-mannered,

17:30.000 --> 17:31.166
and out for blood."

17:32.458 --> 17:33.416
"Beth Harmon…"

17:34.416 --> 17:35.375
[coughing]

17:37.208 --> 17:38.250
[sniffs]

17:38.333 --> 17:39.166
Where was I?

17:40.958 --> 17:42.250
It's all Greek, all of a sudden.

17:42.333 --> 17:44.416
It's okay, I've heard enough.

17:47.291 --> 17:50.916
I don't know why my body
is so intent on sabotaging my brain,

17:51.000 --> 17:53.750
when my brain is perfectly capable
of sabotaging itself.

17:57.375 --> 17:59.083
It's mostly about my being a girl.

17:59.166 --> 18:00.416
Well, you are one.

18:00.500 --> 18:02.083
It shouldn't be that important.

18:03.625 --> 18:05.291
They didn't print half the things I said.

18:05.375 --> 18:07.125
They didn't tell about Mr. Shaibel,

18:07.208 --> 18:10.291
and they didn't say anything
about how I play the Sicilian.

18:11.666 --> 18:13.583
Beth, dear, it makes you a celebrity.

18:13.666 --> 18:15.333
Yeah, for being a girl.

18:15.416 --> 18:16.333
[coughs]

18:21.333 --> 18:24.208
Did you ever think maybe
it's the drinking that's making you sick?

18:25.041 --> 18:25.875
Oh, please.

18:26.750 --> 18:28.875
I've flirted with alcohol most of my life.

18:29.500 --> 18:33.000
If anything, I think it's high time
I consummated the relationship.

18:34.750 --> 18:35.583
To motherhood.

18:44.083 --> 18:44.916
Beth?

18:46.666 --> 18:47.916
We're having a pledge party,

18:48.000 --> 18:49.416
Friday night, my house.

18:50.000 --> 18:51.875
The other Apple Pis
asked me to invite you.

18:53.166 --> 18:55.166
-Friday night?
-7:30.

18:56.125 --> 18:56.958
Can you make it?

18:59.958 --> 19:01.958
[pensive music playing]

19:49.916 --> 19:53.250
[girl] It was really something to see you
in the newspaper all those times.

19:53.750 --> 19:56.708
All those places you've been,
which was your favorite?

19:56.791 --> 19:57.875
I liked Houston.

20:02.875 --> 20:07.208
But now that my rating's up to 1800,
I hope to go to Las Vegas

20:07.291 --> 20:09.583
to play in the US Open next month.

20:09.666 --> 20:11.208
What about the boys?

20:11.833 --> 20:12.958
Are they good-looking?

20:13.500 --> 20:14.708
Do you date any of them?

20:15.875 --> 20:19.083
-There's not really much time for that.
-But if you had the time…

20:20.000 --> 20:22.333
is there anyone you've met
that you'd like to…

20:23.291 --> 20:25.750
-trade rooks with, or whatever?
-[girls tittering]

20:27.208 --> 20:29.666
I mean, I trade rooks all the time,
but it's not--

20:29.750 --> 20:30.916
[girls laughing]

20:31.000 --> 20:32.208
I bet you do.

20:32.291 --> 20:33.791
[man on TV] Now, ladies and gentlemen,

20:33.875 --> 20:36.750
Hullabaloo proudly presents
your favorite band from Turtle Creek…

20:36.833 --> 20:38.541
-Thank you, Dora.
