♪ Baby, you're the one that I love ♪

22:54.333 --> 22:55.958
[upbeat '60s funk music playing]

23:56.666 --> 23:57.500
[man] Harmon?

23:59.041 --> 23:59.916
Townes?

24:00.500 --> 24:01.500
That is you.

24:02.708 --> 24:04.291
My stars! You look…

24:06.291 --> 24:07.125
Wow!

24:08.083 --> 24:08.916
Thanks.

24:09.000 --> 24:10.541
[chuckles] You're welcome.

24:12.791 --> 24:14.333
I thought we might bump into each other

24:14.416 --> 24:16.541
when I saw your name
on the tournament list.

24:16.625 --> 24:18.500
-I didn't see yours.
-I'm not playing.

24:19.000 --> 24:20.875
Chess Review sent me to write it up.

24:21.791 --> 24:24.583
Must confess,
I was hoping to see you here last year.

24:24.666 --> 24:25.833
I was supposed to.

24:25.916 --> 24:28.083
I even paid the fee,
but my mother got sick.

24:28.583 --> 24:31.000
-And I didn't want to come alone.
-She all right?

24:31.500 --> 24:32.333
Fine.

24:32.416 --> 24:33.875
I should have come on my own,

24:33.958 --> 24:37.666
but I told myself that the Open's
not as important as the US Championships.

24:37.750 --> 24:39.208
Oh, no. No, it's not.

24:40.125 --> 24:41.500
But I'm sure glad you came.

24:42.666 --> 24:44.375
It's probably a good idea for me to play

24:44.458 --> 24:46.916
in something other
than the events I pick for the money.

24:47.000 --> 24:50.625
-Looks like you're making a lot.
-Yeah, I guess so.

24:50.708 --> 24:51.625
[Townes chuckles]

24:52.250 --> 24:55.958
Still, you could become
a world-class player, be a real pro.

24:56.458 --> 24:59.125
-I started taking Russian at night.
-Oh, that's smart.

24:59.750 --> 25:01.125
[Beth] Don't wanna plateau.

25:01.625 --> 25:05.125
[Townes] No, plateaus are the worst.

25:05.208 --> 25:08.041
And you're far too old
to be called a prodigy anymore.

25:11.250 --> 25:13.333
I should do something on you
for the magazine.

25:13.833 --> 25:16.416
-I was on the cover last month.
-Of course.

25:16.500 --> 25:19.375
I must have got it mixed up
with the one in Life magazine.

25:21.416 --> 25:23.250
I also work for the Herald-Leader.

25:23.333 --> 25:24.250
In Lexington?

25:24.333 --> 25:26.208
I could do a half-page
on you for Sunday's paper.

25:26.291 --> 25:29.333
-Won't be as big a deal as Life, but--
-Yeah, sure.

25:30.416 --> 25:31.333
If you want to.

25:31.958 --> 25:33.375
I got a camera in my room.

25:34.333 --> 25:35.250
In your room?

25:36.583 --> 25:38.541
Chess boards, too. We could play.

25:40.000 --> 25:40.833
Okay.

25:42.083 --> 25:43.041
Let's go up.

25:45.500 --> 25:47.500
[music continues]

26:01.250 --> 26:02.125
[door closes]

26:10.291 --> 26:12.166
Why don't you sit over by the window?

26:16.166 --> 26:18.791
-Uh, may I…
-Oh, yeah, just toss them.

26:18.875 --> 26:20.000
[film loads in camera]

26:27.041 --> 26:28.375
[camera shutter clicks]

26:29.750 --> 26:30.791
I wasn't ready.

26:32.208 --> 26:33.041
You look great.

26:33.125 --> 26:34.291
[camera shutter clicks]

26:37.291 --> 26:38.291
Scooch to your left.

26:41.958 --> 26:43.041
That's right.

26:44.000 --> 26:45.583
-[film loading]
-[Beth chuckles]

26:47.666 --> 26:48.666
Say…

26:49.416 --> 26:50.458
"Ruy Lopez."

26:51.291 --> 26:53.583
-[camera shutter clicks]
-[laughs]

26:55.083 --> 26:55.916
[film loading]

26:59.375 --> 27:00.666
[camera shutter clicks]

27:00.750 --> 27:02.083
You could go by the board.

27:11.083 --> 27:11.916
Okay.

27:12.500 --> 27:14.000
I see you've done this before.

27:17.291 --> 27:18.458
Do you want me to play?

27:18.541 --> 27:20.166
Sure. Black to move.

27:22.208 --> 27:24.166
-[camera shutter clicks]
-[film loading]

27:24.250 --> 27:25.250
All right, slow down.

27:29.166 --> 27:30.458
[camera shutter clicks]

27:30.541 --> 27:31.583
[film loading]

27:33.041 --> 27:34.666
Yeah, that's more my-my speed.

27:39.125 --> 27:40.000
Um…

27:47.000 --> 27:49.125
-You've grown up, Harmon.
-[camera shutter clicks]

27:49.208 --> 27:50.208
[film loading]

27:50.291 --> 27:51.916
You've even gotten good-looking.

27:54.708 --> 27:58.166
-I don't even know your first name.
-Everyone calls me Townes.

27:58.916 --> 28:02.375
Maybe that's why I call you Harmon,
instead of Elizabeth.

28:02.458 --> 28:04.375
-[camera shutter clicks]
-It's Beth.

28:05.250 --> 28:06.083
[film loading]

28:06.583 --> 28:07.416
I like Harmon.

28:19.708 --> 28:21.083
[Beth clears throat softly]

28:50.833 --> 28:51.916
[door opens]

28:53.666 --> 28:55.875
-Oh, hi.
-[door closes]

28:55.958 --> 28:58.458
-Roger.
-[Roger] I'm not interrupting, am I?

28:59.541 --> 29:01.708
Th-That's okay. Uh, we're just…

29:03.541 --> 29:05.458
Beth Harmon, this is Roger Dione.

29:06.125 --> 29:08.125
Harmon? The chess prodigy.

29:09.083 --> 29:11.083
-I've heard so much about you.
-Nice to meet you.

29:11.166 --> 29:13.791
[Townes] I thought you were gonna play
some baccarat?

29:14.333 --> 29:17.541
[Roger] Thought I'd quit while
I was behind and go read by the pool.

29:17.625 --> 29:20.208
You two carry on.
I'll be gone in a minute.

29:20.291 --> 29:21.791
-[hand slaps]
-[Roger chuckles]

29:24.208 --> 29:25.333
[belt buckle clinking]

29:26.625 --> 29:27.500
[unzipping]

29:28.583 --> 29:30.000
-Let's play chess.
-Okay.

29:34.625 --> 29:36.125
[clears throat] Thanks.

29:39.166 --> 29:40.833
[chess pieces clatter softly]

29:42.791 --> 29:43.625
[Townes] Right.

29:45.750 --> 29:47.208
-Here we go.
-[chuckles]

29:49.958 --> 29:51.333
[Roger] Pleasure to meet you, Beth.

29:52.250 --> 29:53.083
You too.

29:54.958 --> 29:56.125
Dinner's at nine.

29:57.833 --> 29:58.666
Don't forget.

30:04.291 --> 30:05.333
[door closes]

30:07.625 --> 30:10.291
[man on TV] Marge, did your aunt
leave you everything?

30:11.166 --> 30:12.500
[woman on TV] I was her only heir.

30:12.583 --> 30:13.958
Where have you been, honey?

30:14.500 --> 30:16.541
You've been gone for hours.

30:16.625 --> 30:19.458
-Playing chess.
-[woman] I don't wanna talk about it.

30:19.541 --> 30:21.166
-Practicing.
-[man] Okay.

30:21.250 --> 30:24.000
-[TV continues indistinctly]
-[Mrs. Wheatley] That's all?

30:24.791 --> 30:26.791
Yeah, that's all.

30:27.375 --> 30:30.708
[man] Well, it's the perfume I use
that makes me smell so nice.

30:31.541 --> 30:33.750
Do me a favor
and hand me a beer on the desk?

30:35.916 --> 30:36.958
[woman] What do you want?

30:37.541 --> 30:40.250
[man] I think I've got one.
I think I've got a gimmick.

30:41.666 --> 30:44.333
A gimmick is an angle that works for you.

30:44.416 --> 30:46.750
To keep you
from working too hard for yourself.

30:47.750 --> 30:50.250
-Simple.
-[woman] Specifically, what is your angle?

30:50.333 --> 30:51.500
[man] Specifically…

30:53.708 --> 30:55.416
I suppose you've never had beer.

30:57.750 --> 30:59.250
-[woman] All right, Sam.
-Here.

31:02.958 --> 31:03.875
[woman] Come here.

31:07.166 --> 31:09.291
My father used to work here
as a mill hand.

31:09.833 --> 31:14.291
-[man] So did mine. When he was sober.
-Whoa, whoa, whoa. Not so fast.

31:14.375 --> 31:15.416
[man] Now, you're even.

31:16.000 --> 31:17.125
[woman] Now, I'm even.

31:17.916 --> 31:21.083
I was 21 when I took it over.
It had 3,000 workers then.

31:21.166 --> 31:22.708
It's got 30,000 now.

31:23.333 --> 31:26.208
Ran as far as that gate,
now it goes down to the edge of the river.

31:27.208 --> 31:28.750
And I did it all by myself.

31:29.666 --> 31:31.916
-Without Walter, without--
-I'd like another.

31:33.208 --> 31:35.666
-[woman] All by myself.
-You really shouldn't.

31:35.750 --> 31:37.708
[man]
Half of this should make quite a score.

31:39.958 --> 31:40.791
All right.

31:41.458 --> 31:43.708
But if you're gonna have one,
get me one, too.

31:44.208 --> 31:45.833
[man] That's what I had in mind.

31:46.958 --> 31:48.958
[woman] You went out of here
a dirty kid once before,

31:49.041 --> 31:50.291
that can happen again.

31:51.083 --> 31:53.458
[man on commercial]
Escape from clothesline drudgery,

31:53.541 --> 31:55.208
but listen to Jinx first.

31:56.000 --> 31:59.041
[woman on commercial] When you buy
your dryer, be sure you get the best kind,

31:59.125 --> 32:00.583
a gas dryer.

32:00.666 --> 32:03.625
Your most delicate fabrics
are safe in a gas dryer.

32:05.583 --> 32:10.000
See? A gentle stream of warm air
sends the clothes' moisture away.

32:12.833 --> 32:14.833
[pensive music playing]

32:20.541 --> 32:23.375
[Beth] My first match
was against this guy from Oklahoma.

32:24.916 --> 32:26.666
It was all over in two dozen moves.

32:26.750 --> 32:27.583
Ouch.

32:28.125 --> 32:30.458
Then, this guy from San Francisco.

32:31.083 --> 32:32.125
I played the Marshall.

32:33.875 --> 32:37.291
Um, sacrificed my queen,
the way that Paul Morphy did one time.

32:37.375 --> 32:38.916
Mm-hm. One more.

32:40.083 --> 32:41.041
What about, um…

32:41.916 --> 32:43.791
What's his name?
The one you told me about.

32:43.875 --> 32:45.041
Bobby something?

32:45.125 --> 32:48.416
-Benny Watts.
-Yes, him.

32:48.500 --> 32:50.041
No losses, but one draw.

32:50.583 --> 32:53.541
Queens Gambit Declined
is so well respected.

32:53.625 --> 32:55.583
[Beth] I've seen him a couple of times.

32:56.458 --> 32:57.666
Always got a crowd around him.

32:57.750 --> 33:00.250
Well, of course, he's the US Champion.

33:00.333 --> 33:01.291
He's Benny Watts.

33:01.375 --> 33:02.291
[laughs]

33:03.375 --> 33:05.708
[Beth] Some people say
he's the most talented American player

33:05.791 --> 33:06.625
since Morphy.

33:07.583 --> 33:09.625
I read about a game
he played in Copenhagen,

33:09.708 --> 33:11.208
a draw against Najdorf.

33:11.875 --> 33:13.125
That was in 1948,

33:13.208 --> 33:15.333
which means that Benny
was eight years old.

33:16.583 --> 33:19.916
I've seen a picture of him at 13
in front of a whole bunch of sailors.

33:20.458 --> 33:23.416
He played against the entire team
at Annapolis without losing a game.

33:23.500 --> 33:25.333
Sounds like someone else I know.

33:26.125 --> 33:28.916
When I was nine,
I was playing Mr. Shaibel in the basement.

33:30.166 --> 33:32.708
Anyway, I'm not afraid of him.

33:32.791 --> 33:35.166
I don't suppose
there's anyone you're afraid of.

33:36.958 --> 33:38.708
There is one player that scares me.

33:40.625 --> 33:41.458
Who?

33:42.416 --> 33:43.250
The Russian.

33:45.416 --> 33:46.250
Borgov.

33:46.750 --> 33:49.916
[Benny] It's a lot more
of a dynamic game than the Caro.

33:50.000 --> 33:52.958
Which is not the case
with QGD versus Slav.

33:56.250 --> 33:57.458
[coins clanking]

34:04.541 --> 34:05.500
You're Beth Harmon.

34:07.166 --> 34:08.000
[Beth] Yes.

34:10.041 --> 34:11.250
I saw the piece in Life.

34:13.166 --> 34:16.333
Game they printed, that was a pretty one.
The one with you and Beltik.

34:16.833 --> 34:17.666
[Beth] Thank you.

34:19.208 --> 34:21.125
I'm, uh, Benny Watts.

34:21.208 --> 34:22.041
[Beth] I know.

34:22.958 --> 34:25.375
We met a couple of years ago
in Cincinnati.

34:25.458 --> 34:27.041
Didn't meet, but we spoke.

34:28.541 --> 34:30.708
-Cincinnati?
-You didn't play that year.

34:32.208 --> 34:34.583
Okay, I'll take your word for it.

34:35.916 --> 34:37.166
Guess I'll see you tomorrow.

34:38.291 --> 34:39.666
You shouldn't have castled.

34:42.125 --> 34:43.375
In your game with Beltik.

34:46.375 --> 34:47.833
I needed to get the rook out.

34:48.916 --> 34:51.041
Well, you could have lost your advantage.

34:52.625 --> 34:53.500
I don't think so.

34:56.708 --> 34:59.541
He plays pawn-takes-pawn.
You can't take back.

35:01.458 --> 35:03.000
-Wait a minute.
-I can't.

35:03.083 --> 35:05.833
I got an adjournment I gotta go play.
But set it up, think it out.

35:06.500 --> 35:08.708
Your problem is your queen knight.

35:08.791 --> 35:12.458
I don't want to set it up
and think it out.

35:19.375 --> 35:21.375
[pensive music playing]

35:40.041 --> 35:41.666
[Beth] Beltik could have beat me.

35:42.500 --> 35:43.333
But he didn't.

35:43.416 --> 35:45.333
Yes, but he could have.

35:45.416 --> 35:47.291
What's worse is I didn't even see it.

35:48.041 --> 35:51.458
Benny Watts, just by reading
about a player he knows nothing about,

35:51.541 --> 35:52.666
he picks it up.

35:54.208 --> 35:57.291
I was so proud of myself
when I found an error in a Morphy game,

35:57.375 --> 35:59.208
and now someone's done it to me.

35:59.291 --> 36:02.458
Stop thinking about
what might have happened in the past,

36:02.541 --> 36:03.791
and get some sleep.

36:08.166 --> 36:09.125
[sighs heavily]

36:09.625 --> 36:10.791
[whispering] So stupid!

36:13.958 --> 36:14.875
[exhales]

36:17.875 --> 36:19.875
[pills clattering]

36:29.791 --> 36:31.250
[crowd applauding]

36:36.708 --> 36:38.166
Pawn to bishop four, right?

36:39.041 --> 36:40.625
-Yes.
-[camera shutter clicks]

36:47.833 --> 36:49.000
[Benny clears throat]

36:54.625 --> 36:57.125
-[chess clock button clicks]
-[chess clock ticking]

36:59.791 --> 37:01.875
-[exhales softly]
-[pensive music playing]

37:21.541 --> 37:23.791
[sighs]

37:32.875 --> 37:35.625
-[clock continues clicking]
-[intense music playing]

38:39.708 --> 38:41.791
[Beth] I thought he could see
what I was planning.

38:50.875 --> 38:53.958
I thought he could hear my heart beating,
and know how panicked I was.

38:59.333 --> 39:01.083
He still had time to get out of it.

39:05.000 --> 39:08.500
But he took the piece just as I planned.

39:10.666 --> 39:12.791
I went into that game
with a perfect score.

39:14.083 --> 39:17.666
Benny had two draws,
so a draw would give me the title.

39:19.875 --> 39:20.791
I wanted to win.

39:22.041 --> 39:23.375
I wanted to hammer his weaknesses.

39:23.458 --> 39:25.416
I wanted to show that pirate
that I could beat him,

39:25.500 --> 39:27.541
even though I didn't play
the way he thought I should.

39:29.000 --> 39:31.750
Then, he captured my center pawn,
my protected pawn,

39:31.833 --> 39:35.208
the pawn that had held his queen
to her corner for most of the game.

39:36.583 --> 39:37.541
I don't understand.

39:38.791 --> 39:40.916
He forced an exchange of queens.

39:42.166 --> 39:43.000
Oh.

39:43.083 --> 39:44.083
Couldn't believe it.

39:45.791 --> 39:47.625
And then I saw what it meant.

39:48.625 --> 39:51.291
With the pawn gone,
I was open to a rook-bishop mate,

39:51.375 --> 39:53.500
because of the bishop
on the open diagonal.

39:54.000 --> 39:57.333
I could protect my retreating knight
by moving one of the rooks over,

39:57.416 --> 39:59.208
but the protection wouldn't last,

39:59.291 --> 40:01.375
because his fucking,
innocent-looking knight

40:01.458 --> 40:02.791
would block my king's escape.

40:03.875 --> 40:05.916
The more I looked,
the worse it all became.

40:06.000 --> 40:08.000
Caught me completely off guard.

40:08.541 --> 40:10.375
It was brutal.

40:11.916 --> 40:13.916
It's the kind of thing
I did to other people.

40:14.625 --> 40:17.041
Kind of thing that Morphy did,
and I missed it.

40:17.125 --> 40:18.708
I'd been thinking about doubled pawns.

40:19.625 --> 40:21.250
You were thinking about winning.

40:25.333 --> 40:26.333
What did you do?

40:28.416 --> 40:30.000
I needed a counterthreat.

40:30.625 --> 40:33.750
A move that would stop him in his tracks,
but there wasn't any.

40:34.375 --> 40:36.250
I spent half an hour studying the board,

40:36.333 --> 40:39.416
and decided that Benny's move
was even sounder than I thought.

40:40.583 --> 40:42.375
I thought maybe
I could trade my way out of it

40:42.458 --> 40:43.916
if he attacked too fast, but…

40:44.875 --> 40:45.833
he was careful.

40:50.000 --> 40:51.958
I had to retreat, but he kept coming.

40:56.541 --> 40:57.750
I wanted to scream.

40:59.666 --> 41:01.041
You resign, now.

41:02.000 --> 41:03.083
[music intensifying]

41:19.250 --> 41:20.291
Tough game.

41:24.375 --> 41:26.375
[onlookers applauding]

41:27.958 --> 41:29.125
[camera shutter clicks]

41:31.833 --> 41:33.000
[camera shutter clicks]

41:38.708 --> 41:40.458
You'll split the prize money.

41:41.291 --> 41:42.666
You'll be co-champions.

41:43.291 --> 41:46.208
You will still get a trophy,
albeit a smaller one.

41:47.250 --> 41:48.458
It happens all the time.

41:49.208 --> 41:50.208
I made some inquiries.

41:50.291 --> 41:53.666
-The Open Championship is often shared.
